Date: fri 17 Jun 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Thanh Nien News online, Fri 17 Jun 2005 [edited]
<http://thanhniennews.com/print.php?catid=8&newsid=7321>

Viet Nam: Doctor in Hanoi Has Contracted Avian Influenza
--------------------------------------------------
A Vietnamese doctor in Hanoi who treated avian influenza patients has
contracted the disease himself, leaders of the Bach Mai Hospital reported
on Fri 17 Jun 2005. The male doctor had been taking samples from carriers
of the H5N1 avian influenza virus, officials said, adding that his
condition was stable.
The infection took the number of avian influenza victims revealed this week
in Viet Nam to 7 and the number of infections since Dec 2004 to 62.
11 avian influenza patients have been hospitalized at the National
Institute for Clinical Research of Tropical Medicine in Hanoi, the
officials said. The center is also treating 12 suspected avian influenza
cases. Their conditions are all "relatively stable". Although the
development of avian influenza in humans has been less serious than at the
beginning of the latest outbreak in late 2004, its indications are
untypical and changing, doctors at the hospital warned.
The H5N1 avian influenza virus has killed 38 people in Vietnam since it
appeared in late 2003. 12 Thais and 4 Cambodians have also died.
[Byline: L.C.; translated by The Vinh]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The following report states that a 2nd test proved negative and it has not
been confirmed that a doctor in the Bach Mai Hospital has contracted avian
influenza virus infection. - Mod.CP]
